# Day 3 — Recursion on Arrays

Today I used recursion on arrays. The pattern is the same
for every problem — check one element at a time using index i
and move forward recursively.

---

## The Pattern I Learned

```python
def do_something(arr, i=0):
    if i == len(arr):            # base case — stop here
        return ___
    if condition(arr[i]):        # check current element
        return 1 + do_something(arr, i+1)
    return do_something(arr, i+1)  # skip and move forward
```

---

## Problem 1 — Count Elements Greater Than X

```python
def count_greater(arr, x, i=0):
    if i == len(arr):
        return 0
    if arr[i] > x:
        return 1 + count_greater(arr, x, i+1)
    return count_greater(arr, x, i+1)
```

Time : O(n) | Space : O(n)

Mistake I made — I tried checking the whole array at once.
Recursion checks one element at a time using arr[i] only.

